  "prompt": "How does the Aereo antenna work?",
  "response": "Aereo was a company that provided a service allowing users to stream live broadcast television over the Internet. The company used a unique and controversial method to accomplish this by deploying a large number of tiny, individual antennas housed within its data centers. Here's an overview of how the Aereo antenna system worked:\n\n1. **Individual Antennas**: Aereo had thousands of small, dime-sized antennas. Each user was assigned their own antenna when they requested to watch a broadcast. This was a crucial aspect of their legal defense; they argued that, because each user had their own antenna, it was similar to personal use of a home antenna.\n\n2. **Signal Reception**: These small antennas picked up over-the-air broadcast signals from local TV stations. The signals were the same as what users could access if they had their own antennas at home.\n\n3. **Streaming to Users**: Once an antenna picked up the desired broadcast signal, the stream was digitized and sent over the Internet to the user's device. Users could watch live or record programming using Aereo\u2019s cloud-based DVR service.\n\n4. **Time Shifting and Place Shifting**: The system allowed users not just to watch live TV, but also to record it for later viewing (time shifting) and to watch it on devices other than traditional TVs, like computers and tablets (place shifting).\n\nThe legality of Aereo\u2019s service was heavily debated, leading to a significant legal battle. Broadcasters argued that Aereo was retransmitting their content without consent or compensation, while Aereo maintained that its use of individual antennas for each customer was akin to personal use of home DVR systems. The case went to the U.S. Supreme Court, which ruled against Aereo in 2014, essentially stating that Aereo\u2019s service was equivalent to a cable company\u2019s service and should be subject to the same retransmission consent requirements. This ruling ultimately led to the cessation of Aereo's services.",
